body:
These two words actually have opposite meanings. Including something means that it&#039;s going to be part of whatever you&#039;re talking about. Excluding something means it _won&#039;t_ be.

For example, let&#039;s say someone has planned a picnic for Mother&#039;s Day.

Inclusion: &quot;Enjoy the picnic, Mom!&quot;
Exclusion: &quot;Go away, Dad. This is Mom&#039;s picnic.&quot;

Or maybe someone is mailing out a newsletter.

Inclusion: &quot;Let&#039;s make sure we remember the addressees whose names start with Mc and Mac.&quot;
Exclusion: &quot;Remove addressees whose names start with L.&quot;

Programming a data structure:

Inclusion: &quot;I&#039;ll import a parallel processing library so I can speed up matrix multiplication.&quot;
Exclusion: &quot;I&#039;ll comment out the code that detects infinite recursion.&quot;

Perhaps someone wants to state that they enjoy eating fruits.

Inclusion: &quot;I love oranges!&quot;
Exclusion: &quot;Apples are yucky.&quot;

Being multilingual:

Inclusion: &quot;This film has Spanish subtitles.&quot;
Exclusion: &quot;This film&#039;s English audio track has been removed.&quot;

Balancing a raid:

Inclusion: &quot;Fire mages are now able to damage the red dragon.&quot;
Exclusion: &quot;Dragons are now immune to Frost damage.&quot;

And, finally, there is a difference between inclusion and exclusion when dealing with gender discrimination.

Inclusion: &quot;Women are encouraged to join this event.&quot;
Exclusion: &quot;Men are forbidden from joining this event.&quot;
